4. Vault Architecture (SERVER-TOUCHING — NOT ZERO-SERVER)

4.1 Upload Flow
- User authenticates via Firebase Auth (email+password or Google OAuth)
- Session persistence is SESSION
- Email verification enforced — unverified users cannot access vault
- App calls POST /get-upload-url on Cloud Run backend with Firebase ID token
- Backend validates token and returns signed GCS PUT URL
- Client PUTs raw file directly to GCS using signed URL
- Files stored unencrypted at: User/{uid}/original/{timestamp}-{filename}

4.2 Backend Logging
- ZERO explicit logging in success path. No filename, uid, fileSize, contentType logged.
- Only console.error(err) in catch blocks for /get-upload-url, delete-media, get-download-urls
- generate-thumbnail logs only emoji success messages ("Image processed", "Video processed") and console.error
- No user data or filenames logged anywhere

4.3 Thumbnail Generation
- generate-thumbnail Cloud Run service in asia-south1
- Downloads FULL file to /tmp/ for sharp/ffmpeg processing
- Only originalTemp is unlinkSync-ed
- Thumb/preview temp files (/tmp/thumb-, /tmp/preview-) NOT explicitly cleaned up — stay in /tmp/ until Cloud Run instance recycles

4.4 GCS Retention
- NO lifecycle rules or auto-delete policy configured
- Files persist indefinitely until user deletes via vault UI
- ORPHAN GAP: If user deletes Firebase account without deleting vault files first, GCS objects become permanent orphans with no cleanup mechanism

4.5 Vault Quota
- Enforces 25 MB free storage quota per account (DEFAULT_FREE_QUOTA = 25 * 1024 * 1024)

4.6 Vault Fetch Calls
- Vault-related fetch() calls are in uploadSingle, loadGallery, and the download confirm handler — including direct fetch() to signed GCS URLs.
- There is no standalone getUploadUrl or getDownloadUrls function.

4.7 Critical Copy Issue
- vault.html FAQ schema claims "Files are encrypted before upload" — THIS IS FALSE
- Files go to GCS raw/unencrypted
- This contradicts actual architecture and creates legal exposure under DPDP

